Besides, the presence of a spirocarbon atom induces a relative steric strain and allows acid, base or thermal promoted rearrangement of these reactants, yielding new and often unexpected spiroheterocycles.[7–10]

(cid:1) 2019 Taylor & Francis Group, LLC ABSTRACT An unprecedented amine-catalyzed stereoselective reaction of a,a-dicyanomethylidenecarbazoles with indane-1,3-dione and aryl/ heteroaryl aldehydes afforded a series of indanedione-fused ben- zo[a]carbazoles. The plausible mechanism for the formation of the final products result from the above MCR is described based on suc- cessive Knoevenagel/Michael/nucleophilic reactions. The products were obtained in moderate to good yields without the use of any chromatographic techniques. The structures of the synthesized spiro- cycloadducts were confirmed by elemental analysis and spectral data (FT-IR, 1H NMR, and 13C NMR). Supplemental data for this article is available online at on the publisher’s website. Department of Chemistry, Bharathiar ARTICLE HISTORY Received 5 September 2018 KEYWORDS Spirocarbocycles; benzo[a]- carbazoles; indanedione; stereoselectivity; vinylogous Michael addition Indanone-fused heterocycles are well known heterocyclic scaffolds in various alka- loids[11,12] and pharmaceutically active compounds such as fredericamycin, colepho- and yenhusomidine.[13,14] Because mone-D, containing spirocyclic indane-1,3-diones exhibit various biological activities, such as anti-cancer, anti-inflammatory, inhibitors of human papillomavirus and serve as suitable precursors for fenestranes, significant synthetic effects have also been devoted to the synthesis of various indenone fused spiroheterocycles.[15,16]

a,a-Dicyanoolefins have been employed as versatile vinylogous donors in various reactions. The acidity of c-C–H is greatly enhanced when the strong electron-withdraw- ing groups such as cyano groups are attached to C=C bonds, which allows the easy gen- eration of nucleophilic species by in situ deprotonation under mild conditions.[17,18] Vinylogous Michael addition of heteroaromatics with electron deficient unsaturated car- bonyl compounds was reported as a key step in the preparation of many spiro com- pounds.[19] Benzo[a]carbazoles are privileged aryl-annulated carbazoles, found in natural alkaloids and pharmaceuticals with anticancer and antiangiogenic activities, and as photographic materials due to their unique electronic and thermal stability properties (Figure 1).[20,21] Among the various strategies reported for the synthesis of benzo[a]car- bazoles, addition reaction utilizing a,a-dicyanoalkenes as synthon remains fascinating and challenging. One of the most potential strategies for the synthesis and library production of spiro compounds is achieved through multicomponent reactions (MCRs),[22] wherein, mul- tiple and diverse new bonds have been created in highly efficient and atom-economical manner, thus saving time and energy and evading multistep purification of various intermediates. They also offer a straight forward one pot access to distinct and complex molecules as well as small and drug like heterocycles. Figure 1. Selected examples of spirocyclic indane-1,3-dione and benzocarbazoles-based natural and bioactive compounds. K. R. ARYA AND K. J. RAJENDRA PRASAD reactive a,a-dicyanoolefins as synthon for the synthesis of benzo[a]carbazoles,[23] in this paper, we report triethylamine-promoted Michael addition methodology for the highly stereo- selective synthesis of indanedione-fused spirobenzo[a]carbazoles from three-component assembling of a,a-dicyanomethylidenecarbazoles, aryl/heteroaryl aldehydes and indane- 1,3-dione.

The three-component coupling of 1-(dicyanomethylene)-2,3,4,9-tetrahydrocarbazole 1 with indan-1,3-dione 2 and aryl/heteroaryl aldehydes 3 in the presence of triethylamine as catalyst in ethanol condition yielded a single product, imino-spirobenzo[a]carbazoles 4 instead of amino-spirobenzo[a]carbazoles 40 without using column chromatographic techniques (Scheme 1). The structure of the synthesized spiro cycloadduct 4 was con- 1H NMR, and 13C firmed by elemental analysis and by spectral data (FTIR, NMR spectra). Next, we turned our attention toward the optimization study on 4a; selected results are presented in Table 1. Initial efforts employing the ethanol solvent in catalyst-free condition proved disappointing by producing 4a. The use of catalytic amount of mor- pholine afforded the desired product 4a, in 18% (entry 2), indicating the necessity of a in this reaction. Indeed, switching to DABCO and piperidine as catalyst, catalyst afforded the desired product 4a in 31% and 45%, respectively, in EtOH condition (entries 3 and 4). However, carrying out this reaction in triethylamine (0.2 mL) increases the yield of the product (68%) (entry 5). Interestingly, it may be pointed out that the increase of catalytic quantity of Et3N improved the yield simultaneously (entries 6 and 7). Experiments with other solvents [namely, MeOH, CH3CN, and dioxane] were found to be disappointing, as 4a was produced with low yields (entries 9–11). Thus, triethylamine (0.4 mL) in EtOH was found to be the optimized reaction condition among the other conditions screened. Scheme 1. Synthesis of spirobenzo[a]carbazole 4. SYNTHETIC COMMUNICATIONSVR

Two C=O stretching vibrations were assigned to strong bands at 1744 and 1707 cm The 1H NMR spectrum of 4a exhibited two broad singlet peaks at d 9.87 and d 9.43 ppm due to indole NH and imino NH protons, respectively. Ten aromatic protons appeared in the region of d 7.92–6.72 ppm. A doublet at d 4.07 ppm appearing for the C4a proton with a coupling constant value of 11.60 Hz indicative of the trans-stereo- chemistry between the C4a and C4 protons and the C4 proton resonated as a multiplet at d 3.89–3.82 ppm. The C6a and C6b methylene protons were visible as a multiplet in the region of d 3.08–2.78 ppm. A sharp singlet at d 2.44 ppm accounted for the methyl protons at C8 position and the methylene protons of C5a and C5b appeared as two mul- tiplets centered at d 2.07 and d 1.63 ppm, respectively. The 13C resonance signals for (cid:2)1. The resonance signals at d two carbonyl carbons were seen at d 198.6 and 198.0 cm 119.7 and 65.3 were attributed to cyano and spiro carbons, respectively. All the other 13C resonance signals were in agreement with the designated structure. This shows that the reaction of dicyanoalkene 1a with indanedione 2 and aldehydes 3a is completely stereoselective in affording only the trans-stereomer.

With the optimized reaction conditions in hand, we then set out to explore the scope of this reaction using different substrates, 1(a–d), indanedione 2, and aryl/heteroaryl aldehydes 3 (a–c) to give novel imino functionalized spiro benzo[a]carbazoles 4 (a–l) as shown in Table 2. The mechanistic abstract of the formation of 4 is outlined in Figure 2. A plausible mechanism for this three-component reaction is outlined in Scheme 2. Initially indane-1,3-dione 2 undergoes a base promoted Knoevenagel condensation with aryl/heteroaryl aldehydes 3 by the removal of water molecule to yield chalcone inter- mediate I. The vinylogous Michael addition of carbanion II (IIa$IIb) derived from the synthon 1-(a,a-dicyanomethylene)-2,3,4,9-tetrahydrocarbazole 1 to the chalcone inter- mediate I affords the resonance stabilized indane carbonyl carboxy anion intermediate III (IIIa$IIIb). Nucleophilic carboxy anion initiated intramolecular cyclization of intermediate III results the formation of the final imino functionalized spiro stereo- mer 4. isolated yield was obtained without column chromatography. SYNTHETIC COMMUNICATIONSVR Scheme 2. Plausible mechanism for the formation of compound 4. We have synthesized a new series of spirocarbocycle derivatives through vinylogous Michael addition. A new, simple and efficient base-catalyzed three-component assembling of dicyanomethylidenecarbazoles with indane-1,3-dione and aryl/heteroaryl aldehydes for the stereoselective synthesis of indanedione-fused spiro benzo[a]carbazoles was developed. Using this method, a diverse spirocarbocycle library has been rapidly constructed with excellent yields without involving tedious extraction and isolation procedures. This reac- tion not only demonstrates efficient strategy for the synthesis of spiro benzo[a]carbazoles but also demonstrates the synthetic utility of a,a-dicyanomethylidenecarbazoles. All the chemicals were bought from Sigma-Aldrich and Merck and were utilized for the process without further purification. General procedure for the synthesis of indanedione- spirobenzo[a]carbazoles 4(a–l) An equimolecular mixture of appropriate dicyanomethylidenecarbazole 1 (1 mmol), indane-1,3-dione 2 (1 mmol), and aryl/heteroaryl aldehyde 3 (1 mmol) was taken in a 50 mL of round-bottomed flask in EtOH and stirred in the presence of Et3N (0.4 mL) at room temperature for 5 h. The solid precipitate appeared slowly at the end of the reac- tion, which was filtered off and washed with dry ethanol, and it was dried to give pure compound 4 without using column chromatographic technique.
